    {
      "role": "assistant",
      "content": "My apologies, I sometimes get a bit carried away with the whims of the goblin horde! To stick strictly to the formula, you simply need to incorporate the *value* of the shrinkage into the Cost of Goods Sold (COGS) figure. The \"sneaky goblin\" is just a metaphor for the unaccounted-for inventory, which is what we're trying to quantify.\n\nAs for the average inventory part, the shrinkage *directly* impacts it because the recorded inventory count is artificially inflated by the missing stock. If you have a discrepancy, your average inventory needs to be adjusted downward to reflect the true, lower quantity on hand.\n\nThe adjusted formula becomes: **(Recorded COGS + Value of Shrinkage) / (Average Inventory - Value of Shrinkage)**.\n\nThis way, you are dividing the true cost of what you moved by the true amount of stuff you actually had on the shelves. It’s like trying to figure out how many goblins are in the pile when some have slipped away!",
      "source": "target",
